online access with authorization2star  aThis unique collection of essays, accompanied by videos, at last brings a dazzling view of the literary, social, and performative aspects of American Sign Language to a wide audience. The book presents the work of a renowned and diverse group of deaf, hard-of-hearing, and hearing scholars who examine original ASL poetry, narrative, and drama. The videos showcases the poems and narratives under discussion in their original form, providing access to them for hearing non-signers for the first time. Together, the book and videos provide new insight into the history, culture, and creative achievements of the deaf community while expanding the scope of the visual and performing arts, literary criticism, and comparative literature. The videos may be viewed online at ucpress.edu/go/signingthebodypoetic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican Sign Language literature. 0aDeaf authors. 0aDeaf, Theater for the. 0aVisual literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBahan, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauman, Dirksen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBauman, H-Dirksen L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarmon, Kristen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrentz, Christopher B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, W. J. T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPadden, Caro